\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Dont want this relationship to be where you are acting as therapy, and vice-versa. Because I think our base beings go good together, and for me its a matter of keeping that centered.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 FHDM, I\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92m sending this because you\u8217\'92ve sent positive signs regarding FHDMs, open communication, emotional maturity and what not, which is great. My gut instinct is to not send it, because I think our base beings go good together, its simple, its fun, and I think that in itself is healing, and I want to keep that fun and simplicity centered. Sometimes I feel like some of these FHDMs are overwrought, and because of that, they might complicate that simplicity, but that\u8217\'92s not my intent. This is purely a window into Mike\u8217\'92s brain. You don\u8217\'92t need to do anything with it. It\u8217\'92s not an attempt to change you or your behavior towards me. I\u8217\'92m going to keep assuming that you like this stuff, until you say otherwise.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Anyways, these past few months I\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve been doing a deep dive into mental illnesses, both to try and understand your previous relationship, and to try and understand myself. At this point, I\u8217\'92m pretty sure I\u8217\'92m not mentally ill. I suspect that when I was younger, I had a mild case of \u8216\'91quiet\u8217\'92 borderline personality disorder. Evidently a large percentage of people who have it simply age out of it as their brain develops. And these are people who had it so severely that they were hospitalized. The core issue here is a too-small amygdala, which results in difficulty with emotional regulation.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab There was an interesting study which measured BPD emotional sensitivity; videos were taken where a person shows a happy face, and then they change to an angry face. Still frames are taken from the video, so that there is a series of images gradating from happy to angry. The subjects of the study were asked to express their feelings about the emotion expressed in a given still frame. Normal people needed a happy face to go 70% of the way towards an angry face in order to tell when a person was angry. Someone with BPD only needed 30% angry. So, basically, the subject was 70% happy, 30% angry, but the BPD person understood the subject to be angry.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab This hypersensitivity towards other people\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s emotions describes me very well\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 hypersensitivity, with a bias towards the negative. That in itself does not make me BPD. I also don\u8217\'92t think it is a bad trait to have, because it makes me an very empathetic person. But does become bad when it causes emotional dysregulation, as what happens in BPD, and as what can happen with me.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab In the past I\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d judge people harshly when they weren\u8217\'92t as empathetic towards others as I was. Like, part of the \u8220\'93window into Mike\u8221\'94 is that I would have judged the way you reacted the Nastasha situation pretty harshly. Present Mike recognizes that you have a \u8220\'93normal\u8221\'94 proccessing of people\u8217\'92s emotions, and probably Nastasha is more similar to me on the hypersensitivity scale.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Fear of abandonment. Which I do not have. It would SUCK if you decided to break things off, but it would not end my world. Another trait of BPD that I don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t have, is absence of self. I can be overly hard on myself, yes, but there is still a sense of self for me to be hard on. I don\u8217\'92t ever feel \u8216\'91empty\u8217\'92 inside, which is a common trait of BPD. I\u8217\'92m not a chameleon, where I will pretend to like other people\u8217\'92s interests just so they\u8217\'92ll like me back, etc.}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 I\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92m not going to deep dive into this subject anymore, because for one, I don\u8217\'92t feel any of this is something I can\u8217\'92t hurdle myself, and for two, if I wanted more accuracy and knowledge I\u8217\'92d have to go see a therapist, which is not in the cards at the moment. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Phone text last night. Sent the text at like 10. Knew you were out and about, but then my mind went in the direction of, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What does it *mean* if she doesn\u8217\'92t text back? She came home, went to bed}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 -\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What\u8217\'92s necessary for BPD to develop is a brain that is extra sensitive to emotions, plus an invalidating environment. This may explain how three kids can grow up in an invalidating, but not traumatic environment, only one of them grows up with BPD. Thats because only one of them has an itchy trigger finger when it comes to intense, negative emotions.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 There was an interesting study which measured BPD emotional sensitivity; videos were taken where a person shows a happy face, and then changes to an angry face. Still frames are taken from the video, so that there is a series of images gradating from happy to angry. The subjects of the study were asked to express their feelings about the emotion expressed in a given still frames. Normal people needed a happy face to go 70% of the way towards an angry face in order to tell when a person was angry. Someone with BPD only needed 30%. So, basically, the subject was 70% happy, 30% angry, but the BPD person understood the subject to be angry.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 This hypersensitivity towards emotions describes me very well. That being said, I don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t think I am BPD, or, if I was, I now have a significantly more mild version of it, or it is no longer expressed. Evidently a large percentage of people who have it simply age out of it as their brain develops. The core issue is a too-small amygdala, which results in difficulty with emotional regulation.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 When I see someone expressing discomfort, my mind goes into overdrive in trying to understand where they are coming from, and then feel things from their perspective. }}